0","1346–1440":"1346–1440","1346–1437":"1346–1437","1365–1424":"1365–1424","–Male":"Overleden","1437":"1437","1424":"1424","1346":"1346","BET 1377 AND 1412":"van 1377 to 1412","1365":"1365","BET 1377 AND 1437":"van 1377 to 1437","1440":"1440","ABT 1346":"circa 1346","BET 1377 AND 1440":"van 1377 to 1440","Nettlestead, Suffolk, England":"Nettlestead, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1346–BET 1377 AND 1440":"about 1346–from 1377 to 1440","1346–1440":"1346–1440","1346–1437":"1346–1437","1365–1424":"1365–1424","–Male":"Deceased","1437":"1437","1424":"1424","1346":"1346","BET 1377 AND 1412":"from 1377 to 1412","1365":"1365","BET 1377 AND 1437":"from 1377 to 1437","1440":"1440","ABT 1346":"about 1346","BET 1377 AND 1440":"from 1377 to 1440","Nettlestead, Suffolk, England":"Nettlestead, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cobham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of at least three places in southern England called Cobham, in Kent, Surrey, and Sussex."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Cobham was born about 1346, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of James Cobham. She married Phillip Spencer from 1377 to 1412. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died from 1377 to 1440."},"et":{"ABT 1346–BET 1377 AND 1440":"umbes 1346–1377 kuni 1440","1346–1440":"1346–1440","1346–1437":"1346–1437","1365–1424":"1365–1424","–Male":"Surnud","1437":"1437","1424":"1424","1346":"1346","BET 1377 AND 1412":"13